UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199689900792
AB  - A two-commodity intertemporal framework is used to show that, in contrast to the conventional wisdom, both permanent and temporary tariffs may worsen the trade balance of a large country. For a temporary tariff the key condition for this result is a low intertemporal elasticity of substitution in consumption. When a temporary tariff worsens the trade balance the world real interest rate must fall if the tariff-imposing country is running a deficit and rise if it is running a surplus. Temporary tariffs can only worsen the trade balance of a surplus country when international differences in tastes are important.
